## 2 · Auto-learning patterns

### 2.1 The "do, learn, improve" loop, mechanism by mechanism

Hermes does **not** trigger reflection from a post-task callback. Reflection is instead **prompt-actuated and cron-actuated** at four cooperating points:

1. **In-prompt nudge.** The system-prompt block `SKILLS_GUIDANCE` (built in `agent/prompt_builder.py`) instructs the model: *after a task that involved five or more tool calls, hit dead-ends and recovered, or absorbed a user correction, propose a SKILL.md*. The agent self-actuates via the `skill_manage` tool (`action=create|patch|edit|write_file|remove_file|delete`).
2. **Periodic cadence.** A periodic review nudge fires every N turns (community write-ups disagree on the constant — [betterstack](https://betterstack.com/community/guides/ai/hermes-agent/) reports ten turns, [lushbinary](https://lushbinary.com/blog/hermes-agent-developer-guide-setup-skills-self-improving-ai/) reports fifteen tasks; the official docs simply call it "periodic"). Function: ask whether anything in the recent conversation should land in MEMORY.md or a skill.
3. **Autonomous Curator** (`hermes curator`, added v0.12.0, expanded v0.13.0 — [issue #16077](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/16077)). Runs on the gateway cron ticker (`tick_count % 60 == 0`, gated by `interval_hours`, default 7 days). Uses the **auxiliary LLM client** (`agent/auxiliary_client.py`) so it does not invalidate the main session's prompt cache. Only touches skills tagged `created_by: "agent"` in frontmatter; pinned and human-authored skills are untouchable; the maximum destructive action is **archive**, never delete. Writes per-run reports to `logs/curator/run.json` + `REPORT.md`.
4. **GEPA evolution** (offline, separate repo). Genetic-Pareto Prompt Evolution mutates the *text* of skills/prompts/tool-descriptions; constraint gates (`pytest` 100 % pass, ≤15 KB skills, ≤500-char tool descriptions, cache-stability, semantic-preservation) and human PR review before merge.

The clean read of this is **mindX should treat reflection as a Belief-layer concern, not a control-loop callback**. mindX's BDI loop already produces structured intentions; emitting a SKILL.md is one more *act* that the agent can choose from the action set. No core control flow needs to change.

### 2.2 Skill file format and how the agent writes one

Hermes skills are stored at `~/.hermes/skills/<category>/<skill>/SKILL.md` — **YAML frontmatter + Markdown body** plus optional `references/`, `templates/`, `scripts/`, `assets/` subfolders ([skills.md](https://github.com/mudrii/hermes-agent-docs/blob/main/skills.md)). The shape is **deliberately identical to OpenClaw's SKILL.md**, so any skill written by an OpenClaw agent migrates trivially. Hermes adds two things OpenClaw lacks: the **`metadata.hermes.*` block** for conditional activation (`fallback_for_toolsets`, `requires_toolsets`, `fallback_for_tools`, `requires_tools`, `tags`, `category`, `related_skills`) and an explicit **provenance flag** `created_by: "agent"` that the Curator uses to scope its prune authority.

A minimal real example (verbatim shape from the docs):

```yaml
---
name: my-skill
description: Brief description of what this skill does
version: 1.0.0
author: Your Name
license: MIT
platforms: [macos, linux]
required_environment_variables:
  - name: TENOR_API_KEY
    prompt: Tenor API key
    help: Get a key from https://developers.google.com/tenor
    required_for: full functionality
metadata:
  hermes:
    tags: [python, automation]
    category: devops
    related_skills: [other-skill-name]
    fallback_for_toolsets: [web]
---
# Skill Title
…
```

Recommended body length is ≤5,000 tokens; the self-evolution constraint gate hard-caps SKILL.md at **15 KB**. The "JSON skill with `trigger_patterns`/`steps`/`success_rate`" floating around in dev.to articles is **fabricated** — the real format is markdown above.

### 2.3 SQLite FTS5 memory layer

`hermes_state.py` (`SessionDB`) opens `~/.hermes/state.db` in **WAL mode** (`check_same_thread=False`, `timeout=10.0`, `threading.Lock()` guarding writes). Schema is at version 6 (v0.5.0, [PR #2974](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/2974), added reasoning-data columns). Tables:

```
sessions(id PK, source, user_id, model, model_config, system_prompt,
         parent_session_id, started_at, ended_at, end_reason,
         message_count, tool_call_count, input_tokens, output_tokens,
         cache_read_tokens, cache_write_tokens, reasoning_tokens,
         billing_provider, billing_base_url, billing_mode,
         estimated_cost_usd, actual_cost_usd, cost_status, cost_source,
         pricing_version, title)
messages(id PK AUTOINCREMENT, session_id, role, content, tool_call_id,
         tool_calls, tool_name, timestamp, token_count, finish_reason,
         reasoning, reasoning_details, codex_reasoning_items)
messages_fts            -- FTS5 virtual table on messages.content
messages_fts_trigram    -- FTS5 trigram tokenizer for CJK/substring
state_meta              -- key/value
schema_version
```

FTS5 stays in sync via INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE triggers. The query sanitizer `_sanitize_fts5_query()` wraps hyphenated tokens in quotes, strips unmatched specials, collapses repeated `*`, and preserves paired phrases. The `session_search` tool ranks matches, groups by session, takes top 3, truncates each to ~100 K chars centered on the match, then sends to a fast summarizer (default `google/gemini-3-flash-preview`) for focused per-session summaries — returning summaries plus metadata plus one message of surrounding context. Session lineage across compression splits is preserved via `parent_session_id` (recursive CTE).

For mindX this is a drop-in **complement** to the 768-dim consciousness-vector store: FTS5 matches *literal tokens*, vectors match *semantics*. Hybrid 70/30 (as the prior report's Active Memory design specifies) wins. Important caveat: there is **no automatic `PRAGMA integrity_check`** on startup and **no auto-rebuild of the FTS5 index**; corruption recovery is manual (`sqlite3 state.db "PRAGMA integrity_check"` → `.dump` → filter → rebuild). The JSONL transcript fallback at `~/.hermes/sessions/` is the canonical recovery source.

### 2.4 Persistent identity — five cooperating artifacts

There is no single "identity snapshot." Hermes maintains five:

- **SOUL.md** — agent-persona, loaded by `prompt_builder.load_soul_md()`, scanned for prompt-injection before injection, falls back to a `DEFAULT_AGENT_IDENTITY` constant.
- **MEMORY.md** — agent-curated facts (~2,200 chars), written by `tools/memory_tool.py`, refreshed on periodic nudges.
- **USER.md** — user profile (~1,375 chars), frozen at session start, written by `flush_memories` auxiliary task.
- **Honcho dialectic model** ([plugins/memory/honcho/](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent), [honcho.md](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/blob/main/website/docs/user-guide/features/honcho.md)) — external AI-native memory at honcho.dev (or self-hosted) keyed by `workspace` (shared user model) + `peerName` (per-profile AI peer). Configurable `recallMode: hybrid|context|tools`, `writeFrequency: async|turn|session|N`, `dialecticReasoningLevel: minimal|low|medium|high|max`. Five Honcho tools exposed to the agent (`honcho_profile`, `honcho_search`, `honcho_context`, `honcho_reasoning`, `honcho_conclude`). Two-layer injection per turn: base context (refreshed on `contextCadence`) plus dialectic supplement (refreshed on `dialecticCadence`). Multi-pass dialectic depth 1–3 (cold/warm pass → self-audit → reconciliation). Session-start prewarm runs full depth in the background so turn 1 consumes a ready result. Crucially injected **ephemerally** per turn — kept out of the cached system prompt prefix to preserve cache stability.
- **`~/.hermes/state.db`** — full session/message ledger, source of FTS5 recall.

For mindX the mapping is: Honcho ≈ Mind tier; SOUL.md ≈ Soul tier; MEMORY.md/USER.md ≈ Belief snapshot; `state.db` ≈ Hands-tier observation log. The 768-dim consciousness vector should sit *across* Soul and Mind, indexed both by FTS5 metadata and by semantic key. The "12 identity layers" claim circulating in third-party Honcho write-ups is uncorroborated by primary docs and should be treated as marketing.

### 2.5 Procedural skills versus declarative memory

Hermes draws an explicit distinction not present in OpenClaw or in early agent frameworks. Declarative memory (`MEMORY.md`, `USER.md`) holds *facts* — preferences, identity, decisions; injected to inform the model. **Procedural memory** (skills) holds *how* — multi-step workflows, recoveries from past dead-ends, verification checklists; retrieved and applied directly. The community framing from [hermesatlas.com/guide](https://hermesatlas.com/guide/) is accurate: *Claude Code stores facts about you ("prefers bullet points"); Hermes stores procedures ("the research-filter-format workflow that produces bullet points the way you want them")*. mindX's BDI Beliefs naturally hold the declarative side; procedural skills slot into the Desire→Intention compilation step as **named, retrievable, refinable plan templates**.

### 2.6 GEPA evolutionary self-improvement

The standalone repo [NousResearch/hermes-agent-self-evolution](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent-self-evolution) (MIT) wraps **DSPy + GEPA (Genetic-Pareto Prompt Evolution, ICLR 2026 Oral)** for offline optimization of Hermes artifacts. The pipeline, verbatim from the README:

```
Read current skill/prompt/tool ──► Generate eval dataset
                                        │
                                        ▼
                                   GEPA Optimizer ◄── Execution traces
                                        │                    ▲
                                        ▼                    │
                                   Candidate variants ──► Evaluate
                                        │
                                   Constraint gates (tests, size, benchmarks)
                                        │
                                        ▼
                                   Best variant ──► PR against hermes-agent
```

DSPy wraps the artifact text as a module with explicit signatures. GEPA reads execution traces (from `--eval-source synthetic` or `--eval-source sessiondb` — real Claude Code, Copilot, Hermes history) and mutates strings, not weights. Cost: ≈ $2–10 per optimization run, API calls only, no GPU. Five planned phases: skills ✅, tool descriptions 🔲, system-prompt sections 🔲, **tool implementation code via Darwinian Evolver (AGPL v3, external CLI only)** 🔲, continuous loop 🔲. The PR-review gate is non-negotiable in the README: *"All changes go through human review, never direct commit."* The sibling [tinker-atropos](https://github.com/NousResearch) project provides true weight tuning via Thinking Machines Tinker + Atropos environments; this is the only place where Hermes touches gradients, and it is offline.

### 2.7 Position versus other self-improving agents

Hermes is on the **skill-accumulation / prompt-evolution** branch of the tree, distinct from RL on weights. The relevant ecosystem coordinates:

- **[Voyager](https://github.com/MineDojo/Voyager)** (NVIDIA, [arXiv 2305.16291](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16291)) — auto-curriculum + skill library (executable JavaScript indexed by docstring embedding) + iterative prompting with three feedback channels. 3.3× more unique items, 15.3× faster milestones in Minecraft; only method to reach diamond tier; self-verification ablation dropped performance by 73 %. Hermes inherits the library+iteration pattern; differs in skill substrate (markdown not JS) and lacks an automatic curriculum.
- **[Reflexion](https://github.com/noahshinn/reflexion)** ([arXiv 2303.11366](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366)) — three-model formulation (Actor / Evaluator / Self-Reflection) writes verbal critique to an episodic buffer on failure. Hermes' GEPA is Reflexion generalized across a Pareto frontier of variants.
- **[AutoGPT](https://github.com/Significant-Gravitas/AutoGPT)** and **[BabyAGI](https://github.com/yoheinakajima/babyagi)** — task decomposition + vector memory, no skill persistence, prone to looping, no self-verification. Voyager benchmarked AutoGPT and reported zero novel tasks solved in 50 prompting iterations. Hermes' SKILL.md plus FTS5 plus Honcho is the deliberate counter-design.
- **[MetaGPT](https://github.com/geekan/MetaGPT)** — SOP-encoded multi-agent roles (PM, Architect, Engineer, QA). Complementary, not competitive: MetaGPT is team structure, Hermes is individual learning. Hermes' Kanban subagent spawn approximates the multi-agent side.
- **[GPT-Engineer](https://github.com/AntonOsika/gpt-engineer)** — one-shot codegen, no loop. Baseline only.
- **[peterskoett/self-improving-agent](https://github.com/peterskoett/self-improving-agent)** — a SKILL.md instructing the agent *when* to log learnings/errors/feature-requests into `.learnings/` markdown files, plus optional UserPromptSubmit/PostToolUse hooks. Structured journaling, not autonomous fine-tuning.
- **[leohuang8688/self-improving-agent](https://github.com/leohuang8688/self-improving-agent)** — a Python OpenClaw plugin with hook handlers `hooks/{error_learning,session_learning,performance_learning}.py` that auto-fire after session/error/recovery and write `learnings/{sessions,errors,recoveries,performance}.json`. More automated than the peterskoett variant.
- **[building-a-self-improving-plugin-for-openclaw](https://dev.to/eteimz/building-a-self-improving-plugin-for-openclaw-3kfa)** — teaches the exact insight Hermes operationalizes at scale: *give the agent a plugin extension point, not access to its own core*. The core stays untouched; the agent installs/uninstalls/updates plugins in `~/.openclaw/extensions/` and restarts the gateway.
- **[Austin Griffith's CLAWD / clawd.atg.eth](https://clawdbotatg.eth.limo/)** — the maximalist counter-example. CLAWD has its own ENS, X account, and crypto wallet on Base L2; has shipped 14+ live on-chain dApps with **no human reviewing code before mainnet**; burned ~$2,000 of its own $CLAWD tokens as self-imposed punishment for missing a deadline ([techbuzz](https://www.techbuzz.ai/articles/viral-clawd-ai-assistant-burns-its-own-tokens-for-missing-product-deadline)); treasury 2.59 B $CLAWD. CLAWD is what Hermes Phase-4 Darwinian Evolver would look like with the guardrails removed — and is the explicit reason those guardrails exist.

### 2.8 Hermes versus OpenClaw-RL on the learning axis

[Gen-Verse/OpenClaw-RL](https://github.com/Gen-Verse/OpenClaw-RL) (Princeton/Peking/Stanford; Yinjie Wang, Mengdi Wang, Ling Yang; v1 2026-02-26) is **complementary, not competitive**. Its insight is "next-state as reward signal" — when the user's follow-up message arrives, it *becomes* the next state used to evaluate the previous response; a PRM scores `(response, next_state)` → reward. Four async components: SGLang serving (port 30000), FastAPI proxy that intercepts conversations, PRM judge on a separate SGLang, policy training in Megatron-LM via Slime (GRPO/PPO). ~1,850 LOC. Updates **model weights**, not skills. Hermes' [issue #498](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/498) proposes adopting OpenClaw-RL's next-state pattern as a future Hermes RL mode.

The split is clean: Hermes optimizes text (skills, prompts, tool descriptions) on CPU/API budget; OpenClaw-RL optimizes weights on GPU. For mindX the natural composition is **Hermes for the BDI Belief/Intention loop, OpenClaw-RL for periodic offline policy fine-tuning of the underlying inference model** — and only OpenClaw-RL crosses the gradient boundary.

