## 3 · Adaptive patterns

### 3.1 Adapting to user behavior over time

Hermes builds two cooperating user models: bounded local files (USER.md ~1,375 chars + MEMORY.md ~2,200 chars, injected every turn) and the unbounded Honcho dialectic model. Signals consumed include preference statements, correction history (a correction triggers a MEMORY.md edit or a new skill), tool-use patterns, conversation outcomes, formatting preferences, and prior decisions in similar contexts. Honcho's dialectic reasoning fires *after* each turn and derives insights about preferences, habits, and goals. The five Honcho tools (`honcho_profile`, `honcho_search`, `honcho_context`, `honcho_reasoning`, `honcho_conclude`) let the agent introspect the user model at runtime. Profile isolation gives each Hermes profile a distinct AI peer while sharing the user-workspace context — so multi-instance users see consistent self across machines but each Hermes "personality" remembers its own relationship.

### 3.2 Dynamic skill composition and chaining

Skills are surfaced via **progressive disclosure**: `skills_list` returns the catalog with descriptions, `skill_view(name)` returns the full body, `skill_view(name, path)` opens a referenced file inside the skill folder. The agent selects skills at runtime from frontmatter description matching plus conditional-activation hints (`metadata.hermes.fallback_for_toolsets`, `requires_toolsets`). Multiple skills can compose in a single turn. Cron jobs chain via `cron context_from` — job A's output feeds job B for "find this, research this, output this" pipelines.

### 3.3 Adaptive context compaction

[`agent/context_compressor.py`](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent) is the canonical reference. Single-phase summarization with configurable threshold (`compression.threshold = 0.50` default, `target_ratio = 0.20`, `protect_last_n = 20`); fires when context exceeds ~85 % of model window in practice. Preserves system prompts, initial user exchange, most recent N turns. Older middle turns are summarized through `call_llm(task="compression", temperature=0.3)`. `SUMMARY_PREFIX` marks summaries so the agent treats them as background. `_strip_image_parts_from_parts` removes base64 images from middle turns before summarization. The whole compaction surface is a **pluggable Context Engine plugin** since v0.9.0 (PR [#7464](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/7464)).

Hardening landed in Q1 2026: anti-thrashing protection ([#9674](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/9674)), tool-output dedup ([#9677](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/9677)), max_tokens cap reduced from 2× to 1.3×, multimodal safety, adaptive failure cooldown (600 s → 60 s for transient errors, [#9678](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/9678)), smart tool-output collapse ([#9661](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/9661)), structured action-log summaries ([#9663](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/9663)). UX: a tiered context-pressure bar (`◐ context ████░░ 62% to compaction`), a warning at 85 %, and `/compress <focus>` for guided compression. The compaction-death-spiral guard ([#4750](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/4750), closes [#2153](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/2153)) stops the loop where compression triggers → fails → re-triggers. Open issue [#513](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/513) proposes a two-phase Kilocode-style prune-before-compact; not yet merged.

### 3.4 Model switching and resilience routing

`hermes model` flips active provider:model in-place. The resilience stack has three layers ([fallback-providers.md](https://github.com/mudrii/hermes-agent-docs/blob/main/fallback-providers.md)):

1. **Credential pools** — multiple keys per provider; rotation strategies `fill_first` (default), `round_robin`, `least_used`, `random`. On 429 the pool marks the entry exhausted and rotates. `_sync_codex_entry_from_cli()`, `_sync_anthropic_entry_from_credentials_file()` pull fresh tokens from `~/.codex/auth.json`, `~/.claude/.credentials.json`.
2. **Primary model fallback** — ordered `fallback_providers: [...]` in `config.yaml`, tried on rate-limit, server errors, auth failures, connection drops, 429 with Retry-After, stale OAuth, 401 (one-shot refresh before fallback), Anthropic long-context tier 429 (auto-reduce to 200 K context, [#4747](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/4747)). Per-turn primary-runtime restoration ([#4624](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/4624)) — after fallback use, agent automatically returns to primary on the next turn. `run_agent.py:_try_activate_fallback()` (lines ~4987–5125 per [issue #7230](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/7230)).
3. **Auxiliary task fallback** — independent provider resolution for vision, compression, web extraction, title generation, session_search.

Open bug worth flagging: [issue #22277](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/22277) — fallback chain not activated on stream-stall timeouts, retry loop re-hits broken primary. P1 as of 9 May 2026.

### 3.5 Error-pattern recognition

Hermes does *classification + automated recovery*, not learned failure modeling. Concrete adaptations: structured provider error classification ([#5435](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/5435)); empty-response retry with nudge, 3 attempts ([#6488](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/6488)); empty-response recovery for reasoning models MiMo/Qwen/GLM ([#8609](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/8609)); think-only empty-response classification to prevent infinite retries on reasoning blocks ([#4645](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/4645)); adaptive streaming backoff with cursor strip; truncated streaming tool-call detection ([#6847](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/pull/6847)); stale non-stream detection with `stale_timeout_seconds`. Skill self-improvement on failure is text-based, agent-driven, prompt-nudged ("patch when outdated, incomplete, or wrong"). GEPA closes the loop offline via execution traces. Adaptation is largely **reactive** (classify → retry → fallback → compact), not pattern-mining across sessions.

